Bearer + --workspace flags + workspace-routing fallback + per-workspace
session scoping + global adapter registration.

Adds the genuinely-upstreamable subset of opencode-bearer-auth changes.
This patch is independent of any deployment glue and is intended to be
proposed upstream once the API stabilises.

What this adds:
  - `OPENCODE_SERVER_BEARER` env (core/flag/flag.ts) and a Bearer
    response from `ServerAuth.header()` (server/auth.ts). The bearer
    can also be passed via `opencode attach --bearer`.
  - `opencode attach --workspace <id>` propagates through `tui()` into
    `SDKProvider` (passed as `experimental_workspaceID`) and into
    `ProjectProvider` (which seeds the workspace into the project store
    so downstream components -- including `WorkspaceProvider`, which
    reads `store.workspace.current` -- target the chosen workspace).
    Net effect: the TUI's home prompt opens new sessions against the
    workspace named on the command line.
  - `validateSession` honours the workspace argument.
  - Workspace-routing middleware reads `x-opencode-workspace` for ALL
    methods, not just GET/HEAD. The SDK only rewrites header->query
    for GET/HEAD, leaving POST/PUT/DELETE with the header verbatim;
    upstream's server used to ignore the header on those methods.
  - `Session.listGlobal` accepts a `workspaceID` filter and applies it
    as `where SessionTable.workspace_id = workspaceID`. The
    /experimental/session handler forwards the request's `?workspace=`
    query param into this filter (with the routing middleware's
    InstanceState.workspaceID as a belt-and-suspenders fallback).
    Without this, upstream's session-list path keyed on `project_id`,
    which broke workspace-scoped `--continue` whenever multiple
    workspaces shared a project_id -- the common case for
    `POST /experimental/workspace` from a front-opencode running in a
    non-git cwd, since opencode copies the requesting instance's
    `project.id` (often "global") into the new workspace row at insert
    time. Filtering by workspace_id sidesteps the issue entirely:
    sessions get scoped by the workspace they actually belong to,
    independent of whatever project_id happened to be stamped on them.
    Verified in the harness: dispatching three workspaces against the
    same repo produces three sessions with identical project_id but
    distinct workspace_id, and `GET /experimental/session?workspace=<id>`
    returns exactly the session for that workspace.
  - `Workspace.startWorkspaceSyncing` accepts an optional `workspaceID`
    opt; when set (passed by the SyncHttpApi.start handler reading
    `InstanceState.workspaceID`), the dispatch query filters by
    `WorkspaceTable.id = workspaceID` instead of `project_id = projectID`.
    Same shape as the listByProject divergence above: without this,
    `POST /sync/start?workspace=<id>` returns true but never (re)populates
    the in-memory `connections` Map for that workspace, because the
    routed instance's `ctx.project.id` is the worktree-hashed value but
    `WorkspaceTable.project_id` is "global" -- the project_id query
    matches 0 rows, the `for (const ...)` iteration never runs, setStatus
    never fires, and `/experimental/workspace/status` returns []. The
    TUI then refuses to attach with DialogWorkspaceUnavailable because
    `store.workspace.status[id]` is undefined. Restart is the common
    reproducer (the create-path's implicit startSync seeds the Map at
    INSERT, so `/sync/start?workspace=` is only exercised in anger after
    the Map is wiped), but the query is broken for any caller of the
    routed `/sync/start` endpoint regardless of restart. Verified in
    the e2e harness via the 04d-sync-start-workspace regression phase.
  - Plugin-adapter registration is scoped to `ProjectID.global` rather
    than the boot instance's `ctx.project.id`. Plugins load once per
    opencode process but serve requests across many projects (via
    per-request x-opencode-directory); a per-project registration
    scope was unreachable from any request whose project differed from
    the plugin loader's. The fallback in `getAdapter` checks global if
    a per-project lookup misses, preserving back-compat for any
    out-of-tree consumer that registers under a specific project.

Server-side opencode does NOT validate the Bearer -- this patch only
adds the surface area for clients to send it. Deployments fronting
opencode with a JWT-validating reverse proxy can use this; deployments
without a proxy continue to use HTTP Basic via `--password`.

Note: an earlier draft of this patch added a post-`adapter.create`
`Project.fromDirectory + UPDATE workspace.project_id` re-resolve hunk
in workspace.ts. Architect review found it dead-weight once
`Session.listGlobal` filtered by workspace_id -- no downstream consumer
actually requires per-workspace unique project_id, and stamping it
post-create added complexity without changing behaviour. The hunk is
gone; this prose block exists as the paper trail so the next reader
doesn't re-derive the abandoned approach.

